comment_text_display: Hi Brian.  Great video.  I was disappointed in the LG G5 and the Panasonic Z95B this year.  I think LG rushed the G5 to market and didn't take the time refine it as much as Panasonic did.  I hope LG spends more time on the G6 with the release next year and it would be nice if Panasonic would provide a sku that doesn't have the extra sound and an OS other than Firetv (that is if Panasonic will have a model in the US in 2026).  OLEDs are still beautiful displays.  I have a C 42 in my spare bedroom/office and it looks great.  I also love Jennifer Gala's content.  I watch it on my two main plasma displays and it really shows off what those displays are capable of, even though they aren't 4k.

comment_text_display:
A Flagship Fiasco!!!
My Sony Bravia 9 K-85XR90 catastrophically failed within 10 months – a mere 83% of the one-year warranty period. Lucky me, it happened within brand one year warranty. Imagine the joy if it had failed after a couple of months! 😂

The brand graciously replaced the defective unit, proving their commitment to quality or not. Seriously, how does a flagship model implode within a year? What magic materials and manufacturing processes are at play here? 🤔

It's crystal clear, low-grade materials and components were used to craft a subpar product. That's why the brand offers a measly one-year warranty with a laundry list of conditions. Bravo! 👏

Let's redefine 'Flagship' and 'Premium' to mean 'likely to fail within a year' and 'barely meets expectations...🎉"

​​@@EngLit123out of the box: kind of. But after the update and about 3 days later, it's not really noticeable. You notice some minor banding, but it's not noticeable in my opinion. It's like the G4 basically (which was my previous TV).

comment_text_display: Hrmm, I see you completely skipped over Dolby Vision on this set. I have the G5, and Dolby Vision content is displayed so dark that its practically unviewable in any mode except "Vivid" mode which is a mode I never ever thought I would use. SDR and HDR content is AMAZING, but Dolby Vision is hot garbage at the moment on this tv. Also the G5 seems to have memory leaks when streaming local files on the network, I've seen this happen in Emby, Plex, and the built in media player, and it seems to happen more often when viewing (you guessed it) Dolby vision content or another person on reddit found for him it was turning on subtitles . Videos would play fine for anywhere from 5-30 minutes then would start to stutter, audio would drop out for a second here and there, then the tv would black screen and give a message that the app was going to be restarted to free up memory. So far no tv updates have fixed this, I'm currently on Firmware 33.20.69 as I write this, for reference

comment_text_display: Could someone clarify something for me? When he says these TVs don’t support DTS through eARC, does that mean a sound bar that does support DTS won’t output that audio type?
comment_text_original: Could someone clarify something for me? When he says these TVs don’t support DTS through eARC, does that mean a sound bar that does support DTS won’t output that audio type?

comment_text_display: Yes, if your TV does not support DTS & you connect a soundbar via eARC, the speaker will be unable to output DTS sounds from sources connected to the TV. The TV cannot transfer an audio format that it does not recognize to your soundbar. The signal "hits a brick wall" at the television & is transformed to a more common audio format, such as stereo PCM, or there is no audio at all. So use soundbars that enable HDMI 2.1 passthrough, such as the Samsung HW-Q990F or HW-Q990D, Sony BRAVIA Theater Bar 9, and so on.
comment_text_original: Yes, if your TV does not support DTS & you connect a soundbar via eARC, the speaker will be unable to output DTS sounds from sources connected to the TV. The TV cannot transfer an audio format that it does not recognize to your soundbar. The signal "hits a brick wall" at the television & is transformed to a more common audio format, such as stereo PCM, or there is no audio at all. So use soundbars that enable HDMI 2.1 passthrough, such as the Samsung HW-Q990F or HW-Q990D, Sony BRAVIA Theater Bar 9, and so on.

comment_text_display:
They should create some kind of wireless display/audio output/input protocol where game consoles & PC's can transmit video & audio wirelessly to your TV so that you don't even need any HDMI/data cables at all, nor the power chord of the wireless transmitter box.
It's ambitious & expensive, but might be better than only having the option to do wireless video/audio through a box that needs it's own power chord & video/audio cable plugged in, when the zero connect box proves that we do have the technology for a standard wireless video/audio protocol where the box itself isn't required.

Sidenote: Since the zero connect box takes up relatively little power such as compared to the TV itself, it might also be possible to at least remove the power chord from wireless video/audio transmitter boxes by plugging in a (this tech is still only being developed) no-wire power transmitter plug into an outlet in the same room, that transmitter boxes can then receive power from, but the plug would have to be small enough to easily fit on an outlet without needing it's own wire to the outlet too.
comment_text_original:

Sidenote: Since the zero connect box takes up relatively little power such as compared to the TV itself, it might also be possible to at least remove the power chord from wireless video/audio transmitter boxes by plugging in a (this tech is still only being developed) no-wire power transmitter plug into an outlet in the same room, that transmitter boxes can then receive power from, but the plug would have to be small enough to easily fit on an outlet without needing it's own wire to the outlet too.

comment_text_display:
Samsung has been pioneering the One Connect Box for over a decade, consistently refining and perfecting the technology. They’ve even advanced to a truly wireless One Connect Box, delivering 40 gigabits of bandwidth superior to the LGs 30 gigabits , while also achieving lower latency. On top of that, Samsung equips it with four full HDMI 2.1 ports, plus an additional 2.1 port directly on the TV itself, giving users unmatched flexibility and future-proof performance.

Meanwhile, certain Chinese brands shamelessly copy Samsung’s innovations, right down to the name, without bringing anything genuinely original to the table. It’s a clear case of imitation rather than innovation pathetic attempts to ride on the back of Samsung’s decade of leadership and engineering excellence.

1---- Light SPREAD OUT 360 degree. so the Second the light left TV screen" it spread OUT all directions ===>. NO more Black. By the time it lend in our eyes. we receive ALL sorts of light. there is NO Black / blind spot. <=== so the TV manufacture to SELL u an IDEA : OLED = Pitch Black. its marketing scam. LG/ SONY KNOW it all along.
( in fact the Larger the TV, the further u sit. brighter it get. u get MORE light coming from the Black spot).... OUR brain : Identify it AS ----- Black. by the Surounding Brightness. <==== IMAX screen : White. ===> U do NOT need OLED to have Perfect Contrast. In fact OLED does NOT have Better Contrast due to LOW Color volume / Density <==== suffer the SAME issue Projection/ laser TV .

2--Human eyes have 90% warm colors : 60% Red
🛑🛑🛑🛑🛑🛑, 30% Green 🟢🟢🟢, only 10% Blue 🟦.

🔴🔴🔴🔴🟢🟢=🟡🟡🟡🟡🟡🟡

so our eyes WILL treat its DAY time watching Even tho : at home or IMAX our Brain🧠 :" its dark, night time". our eyes👀:" Its Day time" <== That would make OLED almost Useless at 100". 👅👅👅 I confirmed with My best friend who install TVS cable guy.

comment_text_display: Hey, what do you think about the curvature? Is it too much, or is it a good amount? I've never used 800r curvature before. Right now I'm using a 34" Alienware with 1800r curvature, and I think that is just perfect.
comment_text_original: Hey, what do you think about the curvature? Is it too much, or is it a good amount? I've never used 800r curvature before. Right now I'm using a 34" Alienware with 1800r curvature, and I think that is just perfect.

comment_text_display: I think it’s perfect for this size of screen. I think curvature is more a function of the overall size of screen, so for example 1800r is perfect at 34”, however any larger than that and I think the sides of the screen start feeling too far away from you. That personally is my biggest issue with the OLED G9, in that it is 1800R curve compared to their old gen G9 which did 1000R. It’s not that 1800R is good or bad by itself, it’s just a matter of how large the screen is and what kind of curve do you need to keep the sides feeling like they’re not running away from you
comment_text_original: I think it’s perfect for this size of screen. It’s not that 1800R is good or bad by itself, it’s just a matter of how large the screen is and what kind of curve do you need to keep the sides feeling like they’re not running away from you

comment_text_display: Have a G4 65 inch.  The sound is OK.  The thing is all of these TVs are so thin that it’s impossible to put proper speakers that can give you the full range. Sound not complete full range but maybe 80 Hz to 20,000 Hz actually I don’t even think any TVs go down that low so it’s probably more like 200 Hz on the low end.  I use two HomePods the original ones, but you’re about eight years old now and an Apple TV.   I highly recommend using some sort of sound bar.  There are a lot of great options for our sound bars that are $500 or below that sound amazing and will beat your TV sound no matter which flagship model you have.  The A 95L does have good sound for a TV.   Still a sound bar will beat any of these TVs.  I actually wish the TVs had no speakers at all. They can pass on those savings and make the TVs lighter and thinner.   It’s hard to believe people are buying flagship models and using the sound on the TV.   It’s just not that good not bad one out of 10 it’s a four.

comment_text_display:
Very nice comparison. I bought a Phillips 65" 708 OLED two years ago. It's very nice but I've noticed some odd localised bright zones that aren't as bright sometimes. Like for instance in your video one side of your white shirt is very noticeably darker than the other sometimes. But then when I watch it back, the massive brightness difference is no longer there. It's really weird.

It also becomes really visible in news shows (or any show that tends to have large solid coloured graphics) where a block of colour that's supposed to be solid will have a noticeable brightness gradient.

Sorry to turn my comment into a pseudo tech support question. I really just wanted to compliment your nice video :)

comment_text_display: "Perfect motion clarity with no blur" is incorrect even on OLED TVs and their fast response time. You still get motion blur on an OLED and that is entirely down to the sample and hold scanning method all flat panels use. Only CRTs have perfect motion handling due to how briefly the phosphors are lit and that they are scanned line by line, and the entire frame isn't held until it is overwritten by the next.
comment_text_original: "Perfect motion clarity with no blur" is incorrect even on OLED TVs and their fast response time. @@theviewingangleThanks for the reply comment. I’m thinking about picture quality per viewing distance, mainly - straight on, primarily in a sunlit room (morning to noon).

With a smaller screen one can sit pretty close to a monitor and not detect individual pixels / LEDs. The larger the screen (which one sees better from across a room) … one might detect pixels at a viewing distance of 6 to 8 feet but not 10’ to 30’. So with your recent comparison viewing experience could one detect mini-LED pixels when sitting close to a 65 or 70+ inch mini-LED screen?

Thanks again for your post and comments reviews.

comment_text_display:
Why don't anyone take into account that movies almost NEVER uses 100% black? I have a 6 year old Samsung with local dimming and pretty bad HDR dimming. It's not the black level that makes or breaks it for me, it's the dimming of the whole screen in dark scenes. My friend just bought a lower tier QLED from Samsung and nightscenes looked FAR better but the actual black levels are about the same. All around the PQ was far better than my old tv. People are always mesmerized by demo trailers on OLED in the stores (my wife included) but the trailers are always ment to show the OLED at its best. A movie or tv-show never looks like that.

For me "the movie look" is far more important than inky blacks. It just doesn't look natural to me. Sure in animated films it looks awesome but that takes me to the other point - games! They look far better on an OLED in comparison since most games use the whole array of blacklevels. I've tested Ori on Xbox Series X on an Oled with 120hz and it looked and felt AMAZING as you say in the video about response time.

For me, nothing beats a good projector when it comes to movies!

comment_text_display:
The LG G5 you’re talking about peaks around 2400 nits. That’s VERY bright. But it pales in comparison to modern Mini-LEDs that are hitting 4000-5000 nits of brightness.

Not saying 2400 isn’t enough to clear the brightness in most rooms. Its absolutely more than enough. Even my LG G3 peaks well under 2000 nits is bright enough.

Where I think a lot of reviewers, including me, get hung up on OLED brightness vs Mini-LED is in SDR content. What most people watch. On top of that, SDR + Filmmaker mode. That’s the biggest difference in brightness between the two technologies. Granted, modern OLEDs this is practically a non-issue. But not every OLED is W-OLED or QD-OLED. So there’s still caveats needed IMO. But give it 2ish years and that talking point will go away.

comment_text_display:
We say it because it matters to some, me included. Big reason why reviewers want more brightness in an OLED is because we typically watch content in Filmmaker modes. Pulls that brightness way down. We want that mode to be brighter without ruining the integrity of the overall image.

But I agree, OLEDs have enough peak brightness for basically any room. Mine are never at 100%

comment_text_display:
”Film Grain” is a technique added to reduce banding and make movies look more filmic.

It is not a bi-product of the TV Tech, but there are some signal issues known on LG OLED that can cause film grain when using Limited / Full mismatch and it is fixed if the signal is mapped to Limited/Limited or Full/Full.

Thanks for taking the time to watch my video and for commenting and being part of my community! 🥰❤️
comment_text_original:

It is not a bi-product of the TV Tech, but there are some signal issues known on LG OLED that can cause film grain when using Limited / Full mismatch and it is fixed if the signal is mapped to  Limited/Limited or Full/Full.

comment_text_original: @@EverythingOLEDcopy that mate have you had some time to think on the best game optimzer  pre set using dynamic tone mapping settings video you made that will give the best pop to your image?

comment_text_display:
I don’t personally use DTM, but sharpness 30-35 is great 🥰

If you only want to add very slight sharpness, then opt for 28 instead.

For older gaming consoles sharpness 35-50 is a good choice, super resolution could also be a game changer to make games have a slight soft look to them when you would prefer more sharpness.

SR - HIGH will up the scaled resolution output closer to 2160p

SR - MED will up the scaled resolution output closer to 1600p

SR - LOW will up the scaled resolution output closer to 1200p

At least thats what it looks like when I’ve done some extensive testing 🥰

comment_text_display:
If your able to still buy an LG C4 and at a larger size for the same price that would be preferred. They are more then anyone will ever need and they have the same experience overall.

LG C5 is better in some areas but I still recommend to save a few bucks and get the older model. C4 has all of C5s features now with the new patch.

C5 has a refresh rate of 144hz just like the C4, the only real difference is in brighter luminance.

Find what suits you most friend, but I recommend saving a little and getting a larger panel 😇👍

comment_text_display: I took into consideration, my room lighting and things that might minorly annoy me to the point of my OCD going off. I would honestly rather stick with a W-OLED or Tandem OLED because they have polarizers to help it retain the perfect blacks in ambient lighting. I don't like to live in a dark environment 24/7, so I feel safe with an LG C5 on my budget. I've liked what I've seen. webOS 25 is much better than the interface used to be so many years ago, While I can control the lighting in my room, I would rather take the safe route of spending 1,700$+ - knowing I'll get those deep blacks I want for Horror and Action films - rather than splurge on a QD-OLED because I'm afraid of that black level raise in general, and feel like I have to go back to the store. Once QD-OLED figures out a way to get rid of their issues, I'll buy one, but for now, Tandem OLED is the technology I want to save my money for.

comment_text_display:
Here in my country, the price difference between a 65-inch OLED and a 77-inch one is just insane — it’s almost double the price, which makes no sense. I know this isn’t the case in other countries like the USA.
Yesterday, I was torn between the LG C5 65-inch and the TCL C8K 77-inch (which was much cheaper). I sat in front of both for nearly an hour and a half trying to decide, and honestly, I couldn’t see much difference in picture quality or black levels. Since I mainly use my TV for gaming, both are great options.
In the end, I realized that if I went with the LG, I’d probably regret not getting the bigger size — it just looked so small! Size really matters to me, so after a lot of thinking and comparing, I decided to go with the 75-inch TCL C8K.
I’m really happy with my choice. I know I would have regretted missing out on the larger screen much more than losing a bit of pure blackness or contrast.

comment_text_display:
Great head to head.

The G5 almost looks 3D in comparison to the TCL with some content - it just has that picture depth that the Mini-LED can't replicate. Obviously if you don't have them head to head the TCL looks a mighty fine TV for the price.

TCL will capture most of the Samsung LCD market and it's no doubt Samsung are in the biggest danger of seeing their market share collapse as TCL (and Hisense) are killing them on the price to picture quality ratio.

comment_text_display:
Thanks so much for watching and for the great questions! The reliability and longevity concern with TCL is a very valid one. While it's tough to say for sure without years of use, I can say that TCL's build quality and general performance feel very solid, and they've made huge strides in recent years.

As for the "V" on the LG, that's a small standby power indicator light. It just lets you know the TV is in standby mode and ready to be turned on with the remote. Great eye for detail!

comment_text_display: Both the TCL C7K and the Hisense U8Q are excellent Mini-LED TVs, but the Hisense U8Q is the more premium and technically superior TV, while the TCL C7K is the better value buy. The Hisense U8Q is positioned as a flagship model, boasting a higher peak brightness (up to 5000 nits), significantly more local dimming zones (up to 6000+ on larger models), and a more advanced Hi-View AI Engine Pro processor. It also features a more powerful 4.1.2 channel 90W sound system. The TCL C7K, while still a fantastic TV with a high brightness of around 3000 nits and a 144Hz panel, is positioned in a lower price bracket. Its value proposition is offering high-end features at a more accessible price point. Therefore, if you are looking for the absolute best picture and sound quality and your budget allows, the Hisense U8Q is the better buy. If you are looking for the best performance-to-price ratio in a Mini-LED, the TCL C7K is the better buy.
comment_text_original: Both the TCL C7K and the Hisense U8Q are excellent Mini-LED TVs, but the Hisense U8Q is the more premium and technically superior TV, while the TCL C7K is the better value buy. The Hisense U8Q is positioned as a flagship model, boasting a higher peak brightness (up to 5000 nits), significantly more local dimming zones (up to 6000+ on larger models), and a more advanced Hi-View AI Engine Pro processor. It also features a more powerful 4.1.2 channel 90W sound system. The TCL C7K, while still a fantastic TV with a high brightness of around 3000 nits and a 144Hz panel, is positioned in a lower price bracket. Its value proposition is offering high-end features at a more accessible price point. Therefore, if you are looking for the absolute best picture and sound quality and your budget allows, the Hisense U8Q is the better buy. If you are looking for the best performance-to-price ratio in a Mini-LED, the TCL C7K is the better buy.

I just went from Samsung 58" the first large plasma under $2000, last spring to a 77" s90 OLED that I got for $2000. I love it, and I'm addicted to the black levels. My take on 8K, fux it. I'm not a gamer, and 99.9% of the content I watch IS STILL 1080p ... AND ... even the 1080 is very often excessively compressed on my cable and satalite TV, and streaming is hit or miss as well. (People paying Netflix a premium for 4K content are very often getting less, sometimes only 720). They might be telling you it's 4K but check your signal for true specs 😮.
Let me restate it this way. 4K TVs have been common for 10 years and 99.9% of all my content is still 1080p or less! Only a few of my blu-ray are 4K. If I were to buy an 8K TV now, it will be buried in the landfill long before I get anywhere near 5% of my content in 8K. So what's the point?

comment_text_display: As a retired TV engineer, I can talk to you about TV displays. We started in the 1940 with B/W crts and then color crts, and BOTH of them suffered from Burn in. Then came the gas discharge displays (plasma) that had exceptional contrast, but the burn in problem was worse, and the power consumption was high. Then came OLEDs, also with exceptional contrast and STILL with a Burn In problem. To us engineers, the advent of LCDs Monitors was a BLESSING! At last, a monitor that can be kept powered up 24/7/365 ! And those are the ones in TV Studios and Production Houses. OLEDs are ONLY used for color grading and are turned off immediately after the job being done is finished. That's the reason I DON'T recommend OLEDs to anyone! I always say that when the "O" in oled is substituted for an "I" for inorganic, then I will recommend those ILEDs.
comment_text_original: As a retired TV engineer, I can talk to you about TV displays. We started in the 1940 with B/W crts and then color crts, and BOTH of them suffered from Burn in. Then came the gas discharge displays (plasma) that had exceptional contrast, but the burn in problem was worse, and the power consumption was high. Then came OLEDs, also with exceptional contrast and STILL with a Burn In problem. To us engineers, the advent of LCDs Monitors was a BLESSING! At last, a monitor that can be kept powered up 24/7/365 ! And those are the ones in TV Studios and Production Houses. OLEDs are ONLY used for color grading and are turned off immediately after the job being done is finished. That's the reason I DON'T recommend OLEDs to anyone! I always say that when the "O" in oled is substituted for an "I" for inorganic, then I will recommend those ILEDs.

comment_text_display:
​​@@BookClubDisaster

I'm not someone who earns a lot of money, but buying an audiovisual product is a passion purchase; I do what's necessary to treat myself and get quality.

To get into the LCD debate, I'd rather get a 65-75-inch Bravia 9 than a 98-inch Hisense or TCL, which aren't at all on par with the Sony in terms of fidelity, upscaling, etc. It's the same price, but my value for money isn't about sacrificing fidelity for screen size.

Again, for the same price or even less, I prefer image fidelity, even if it means going smaller (55, 65, or 77 inches), rather than having an average, so-called immersive rendering at 83, 98, or more than 100 inches.

If you're going to get a 100-120 inch projector, you might as well get a quality video projector (at $3,000, there's a top-notch Epson laser projector and other models), and lower the blinds for a total cinematic immersion.

You have to know what you're buying. Someone tells me they like photography, I'm not going to steer them towards a $1,000 smartphone, I'm going to tell them to get a $1,000 camera.

comment_text_display: I remember both Sony and Samsung concluding that OLED had no real future like 15 years ago.  They both had research in OLED and other technologies and both concluded that OLED was too expensive and didn't have the long term potential to really develop long term.  A better technology would likely come along sooner rather than later and make OLED moot.  This is why both companies dropped the tech to continue research in other display technologies at pretty much the same time.  LG was the only one that stuck with OLED.  Turns out OLED had a longer shelf life than expected, but in the end it sounds like both Samsung and Sony were correct in their conclusions, and it is now becoming reality.  The Chinese, like the Koreans and Japanese, came to the same conclusions which is why they never bothered with OLED.  I'm about to buy my first OLED just in time for the end (?).

comment_text_display: Dude. A while back I had an issue with an 83” A90J. I don’t think it was common, but apparently they used to join to halves together to form the panel in the manufacturing process, and mine had this faint but visible line running vertically down the center of the screen. I could see it in almost all content, and because I knew it was there my eye was always drawn to it. After about a month of emailing Sony pictures I finally got them to see it and admit it wasn’t normal. So they offered me: Full refund or replacement. At the time, the X95K miniLED was new and exciting. Boasting extreme brightness and awesome local dimming. The 85” offered the most zones and was supposed to have minimal to no blooming at all. So I did it. Immediately upon turning the TV on I saw all of this terrible backlight bleeding into the black screen around the Sony logo. Whatever. I thought it was just that local dimming wasn’t engaged. Boy was I wrong! Some of the worst blooming I ever saw. In the actual content itself, and bleeding out all into the black bars even with local dimming on high. I thought for sure it was defective. Sony couldn’t deny the horrors that were the pictures I sent them, so they replaced it and again - maybe even worse this time - it was plagued with terrible blooming. Went back to OLED on my hands and knees after that. Kissed its feet. Begged for forgiveness and will never look back. I’m just as curious as everyone else to see microLED hit the consumer market. Maybe then, but until then, OLED all day long

comment_text_display:
I'm going to send you both the same message on your Fomo and Brian channels.

I don't believe OLED will disappear like Plasma.

Some will stop, like Panasonic, but I think LG will continue, Sony will continue, and Samsung too, if there's still market share to be gained.

They may follow Sony's path, mainly downsizing to 55-65 inches (perhaps up to 77 inches), to offer a reasonable price to ensure a certain sales volume, without harming people who are looking for pure OLED quality.

And alongside this, they will develop LCD to offer very large sizes in this technology, at prices close to a "small" OLED.

OLED isn't going away; it'll still be around in smartphones, gaming monitors, PCs, cars, etc.

At IFA in Berlin Sony put the B8 II next to the reference monitor in studio demonstration, and the RGB led prototype hidden behind a curtain, they did not put the Bravia 9.

And, TCL has started production of inject-printed OLED, initially in small formats to 2026, and is considering how to enter/position itself in the TV market by 2027 (at very reasonable prices).

I hope the two technologies will continue to coexist and offer the best to consumers.

Take care :)

comment_text_display: Reference colour performance levels are determined by black level performance. It’s pretty hard to beat OLED which literally switches pixels off, resulting in zero light emission. With these perfect blacks we get fantastic contrast and vibrant, saturated colors that are natural looking. We get picture performance which does not drop off when you are not seated right in front of the screen. The reason we don’t see much change in the newer models, is because the picture is already close to perfect. I would rather have an 85” OLED with an essentially perfect picture than a 115” TV with a far less perfect picture. That’s just me.

comment_text_display: Thanks for this video, you are very honest, not many are like that.  Not sure if some people are aware, doubling the nits doesnt double our precieved brightness.  Nits are linear, however, our precived brightness is logarithmic.  That is to say doubling the nits from 1,000 to 2,000 would  be around a 20-25% increase in precieved brightness.  There is also a much larger increase in brightness (precieved brightness) from going from 1 nit 101 nits compared to 1,000 nits vs 2k nits.

comment_text_display:
The perfect review I was looking for. A lot of reviewers go way too in depth about nits and all this other technical stuff that in the long run doesn't always matter... Just wanted a simple "Is the picture good and will it do the job, yes or no?".

I had a C1 55 inch which I gave to my in-laws a few years ago when we moved and I also have a S95C 65 inch which we had in our flat, and with SDR content the newer Samsung didn't always look great, sometimes too bright for my liking. I was watching boxing on the C1 last night during our visit and the picture was still beautiful. Looked crisp and often felt, along with my wife, that we preferred the picture that gave over our Samsung - it just all boils down to what you prefer and what looks good so thank you. I don't think you can go wrong with a C Series, I think they're great value - the average consumer wouldn't tell much difference.

comment_text_display:
In this comparison, I find the C5 better, lol..

The G5 delivers more brightness, but not correctly. The yin-yang between very dark and very light isn't optimal.

At first glance, the G5 is more dynamic, but it seems less precise in use.

The color volume also seems better on the C5 (surprisingly).

The details also stand out better.

The G5 looks more like a Tandem RGB prototype that LG hasn't fully mastered than a truly premium TV like the

B8II, the Z95B, and the S95F. If I had to recommend an LG OLED TV to a friend with a ~2,000€ (£$) budget, I'd say the 55C5 + professional SDR/HDR calibration, rather than the 55G5 straight out of the box.

PS: The QD Oled remains superior to the Tandem at the moment T, let's see what happens next and the new technologies that are coming and will further shake up the market (TCL Injekt print Oled, RGB Miniled etc).

B8II, the Z95B, and the S95F. If I had to recommend an LG OLED TV to a friend with a ~2,000€ (£$) budget, I'd say the 55C5 + professional SDR/HDR calibration, rather than the 55G5 straight out of the box.

PS: The QD Oled remains superior to the Tandem at the moment T, let's see what happens next and the new technologies that are coming and will further shake up the market (TCL Injekt print Oled, RGB Miniled etc).
